[[File:China Shanxi.svg|thumb|right|200px|The blast occurred pre-dawn in a mine in [[Gujiao]] city near [[Taiyuan]], the capital of [[Shanxi]] province of [[People's Republic of China|China]].]]
{{wikinews|At least 73 dead after blast in Chinese coal mine}}
The '''Shanxi mine blast''' ({{zh|t=<U+5C71><U+897F><U+5C6F><U+862D><U+7164><U+7926><U+4E8B><U+6545>|s=<U+5C71><U+897F><U+5C6F><U+5170><U+7164><U+77FF><U+4E8B><U+6545>}}) was a pre-dawn explosion that occurred in a mine in [[Gujiao]] city near [[Taiyuan]], the capital of [[Shanxi]] province of [[People's Republic of China|China]] on 21 February 2009. Four hundred and thirty six were in the mine at the time of the explosion. According to the state-run [[Xinhua News Agency]], rescue efforts concluded at 6 p.m. ([[China standard time|CST]]), February 22 with all trapped miners located; the death toll was 74, with 114 in the hospital and five in critical condition.<ref name="<U+5C71><U+897F><U+201C>2<U+2022>22<U+201D><U+77FF><U+96BE><U+83B7><U+6551><U+8005><U+8BB2><U+8FF0><U+60CA><U+9B42><U+4E00><U+523B>">{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/newscenter/2009-02/22/content_10871283.htm|title=<U+5C71><U+897F><U+201C>2<U+2022>22<U+201D><U+77FF><U+96BE><U+83B7><U+6551><U+8005><U+8BB2><U+8FF0><U+60CA><U+9B42><U+4E00><U+523B>|date=2009-02-22|accessdate=2009-02-23|publisher=[[Xinhua News Agency]]}}</ref> Many of the injured are being treated for [[carbon monoxide poisoning]]. The death toll indicates that this is the most lethal accident reported in China's mining industry since December 2007, when 105 people died in a mine explosion<U+2014>that accident also took place in Shanxi.<ref name="73 killed in China mine blast">{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2009/0222/china.html|title=73 killed in China mine blast|date=2009-02-22|accessdate=2009-02-22|publisher=[[Raidi<U+00F3> Teilif<U+00ED>s <U+00C9>ireann|RT<U+00C9>]]}}</ref>

==Accident details==
The pre-dawn explosion occurred at 2:17 a.m. ([[China standard time|CST]]) as 436 workers were in the Tunlan Coal Mine in Gujiao city.<ref name="NYT">{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/23/world/asia/23miners.html?hp|title=At Least 74 Miners Dead in China Blast|last=Wong|first=Edward|date=2009-02-22|publisher=''[[New York Times]]''|accessdate=2009-02-22}}</ref><ref name="73 miners die, 113 injured in China mine blast"/><ref name="Boston Globe: 73 miners die, 113 injured in China mine blast"/><ref name="73 workers die, 113 injured in China mine blast">{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2008770602_apaschinamineaccident.html|title=73 workers die, 113 injured in China mine blast|date=2009-02-22|accessdate=2009-02-22|publisher=''[[The Seattle Times]]''}}</ref> [[Xinhua]] reported that over four hundred men were working when the explosion occurred but that most escaped unhindered and unhurt. One hundred rescuers worked at the scene in Gujiao city as dozens of miners remained trapped.<ref name="Toll climbs in China mine blast"/> [[China Central Television|China Central TV]] (CCTV) broadcast footage of rescuers in orange suits and red helmets with headlamps entering an elevator where they were lowered into the mine shaft as injured miners were taken into ambulances.<ref name="73 miners die, 113 injured in China mine blast"/><ref name="Boston Globe: 73 miners die, 113 injured in China mine blast"/><ref name="Toll climbs in China mine blast"/> A fire in the shaft was said to be blocking the progress of the rescuers.<ref name="73 miners die, 113 injured in China mine blast"/><ref name="Toll climbs in China mine blast"/> There were also reports of trapped miners using mobile phones to call relatives to discuss their plight.<ref name="Toll climbs in China mine blast">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7904122.stm|title=Toll climbs in China mine blast|date=2009-02-22|accessdate=2009-02-22|publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref>
A two-minute silence is planned in recognition of the dead on the 25th of February.

==Shanxi Coking==
The involved mine is owned by [[Shanxi Coking Co.|Shanxi Coking Coal Group]], one of China's largest producers of [[Coke (fuel)|coking coal]], a material used in the production of [[steel]].<ref name="73 miners die, 113 injured in China mine blast"/> The company operates twenty-eight mines. No accidents were reported at the Tunlan mine in the previous decade before this incident,<ref name="73 miners die, 113 injured in China mine blast"/> and it consequently was considered a safe mine at which to work.<ref name="NYT"/> The mine produces five million tons of [[Coke (fuel)|coking]] coal per year.<ref name="73 miners die, 113 injured in China mine blast"/><ref name="Boston Globe: 73 miners die, 113 injured in China mine blast"/>

==Mining in China==
{{seealso|Coal power in China}}

China has the world's deadliest mining industry, with the deaths of 3,200 people reported in 2008.<ref name="Toll climbs in China mine blast"/> This represents a 15% decline from the previous year.<ref name="73 miners die, 113 injured in China mine blast"/><ref name="73 miners die, 113 injured in China mine blast">{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/02/22/AR2009022200205.html|title=73 miners die, 113 injured in China mine blast|date=2009-02-22|accessdate=2009-02-22|publisher=''[[The Washington Post]]''}} {{Dead link|date=August 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref><ref name="Boston Globe: 73 miners die, 113 injured in China mine blast">{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/news/world/asia/articles/2009/02/22/44_miners_dead_others_trapped_in_china_mine_blast/?rss_id=Boston.com+--+Latest+news|title=73 miners die, 113 injured in China mine blast|date=2009-02-22|accessdate=2009-02-22|publisher=''[[The Boston Globe]]''}} {{Dead link|date=August 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref><ref name="73 workers die, 113 injured in China mine blast"/> Government figures show that nearly 80% of China's 16,000 mines are small-scale, illegal operations.<ref name="The Associated Press: 73 workers die, 113 injured in China mine blast">{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gI17C6PKAYIuAfZP89d9AVKnH2rgD96GGC5G0|title=73 workers die, 113 injured in China mine blast|date=2009-02-22|accessdate=2009-02-23|publisher=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref>

